//JPA (Java Persistence API)
  JPA is a specification (standard) for object-relational mapping (ORM) in Java.
  It defines interfaces, annotations, and rules for persisting Java objects into a database.
  JPA itself does not provide an implementation; it only specifies how persistence should work.
  It requires an implementation such as Hibernate or EclipseLink.
  It provides portability, allowing applications to switch between different JPA providers with minimal code changes.

  Hibernate
  Hibernate is an ORM framework and one of the most popular implementations of JPA.
  It provides the actual functionality to map Java objects to database tables.
  Hibernate supports additional features beyond JPA, such as caching, lazy loading, and advanced query capabilities.
  It can be used with or without JPA.
  It reduces the need to write SQL by generating SQL queries automatically.
  
  Spring Data JPA
  Spring Data JPA is a Spring Framework module built on top of JPA.
  It simplifies database operations by reducing boilerplate code.
  It automatically provides CRUD operations through repository interfaces like JpaRepository.
  It uses a JPA provider (such as Hibernate) to interact with the database.
  It supports features like custom query methods, pagination, sorting, and auditing with minimal coding.